        <h2 class="left-heading destination-section-heading">Southern Valley of Fire Formations</h2>
        <p>Further northeast of Las Vegas is the Valley of Fire State Park with striking red rock scenery and many brilliant formations and hiking trails.</p>
        <p>At the southern end of the park near the entrance are four rock formations clustered together, including the fascinating petroglyph-covered <strong>Atlatl Rock</strong>, the small <strong>Arch Rock</strong>, the gorgeous Firecave, and the strange Beehives formation.</p>
        <p>Further down this road are the Seven Sisters Rock formations and the incredible <strong>Elephant Rock</strong>, which actually looks strikingly like an elephant. All of these formations can be seen with extremely short walks, the longest being the 0.3 miles (0.5 km) round-trip to see Elephant Rock. Just a short 0.4 mile (0.6 km) round-trip walk from the Visitor Center is the interesting Balanced Rock formation.</p>
    </section>



